05095nam a22008415i 9780812209822DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1024042249  a(OCoLC)1037944655  a(OCoLC)1041982266  a(OCoLC)1046610933  a(OCoLC)1047000938  a(OCoLC)1049662501  a(OCoLC)1054881065  a97808122098227 a10.9783/97808122098222doi  a(DE-B1597)449846  a(OCoLC)979576341  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aF3351.S215 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a320.09842231 aShakow, Miriam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAlong the Bolivian Highway :bSocial Mobility and Political Culture in a New Middle Class /cMiriam Shakow. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Ethnography00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Language -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Formation of a New Middle Class -- tChapter 2. The Intimate Politics of New Middle Classes in Sacaba -- tChapter 3. Middling Sacabans Respond to Evo and MAS -- tChapter 4. Condemning Clientelism -- tChapter 5. Laments of Betrayal -- tChapter 6. Middle Classes and Debates over the Definition of Community -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tFamily Tree of Doña Saturnina Ramírez -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlong the Bolivian Highway traces the emergence of a new middle class in Bolivia, a society commonly portrayed as the site of struggle between a superwealthy white minority and a destitute indigenous majority. Miriam Shakow shows how Bolivian middle classes have deeply shaped politics and social life. While national political leaders like Evo Morales have proclaimed a new era of indigenous power and state-led capitalism in place of racial exclusion and neoliberal free trade, Bolivians of indigenous descent who aspire to upward mobility have debated whether to try to rise within their country's longstanding hierarchies of race and class or to break down those hierarchies. The ascent of indigenous politics, and a boom in coca and cocaine production beginning in the 1970s, have created dilemmas for "middling" Bolivians who do not fit the prevailing social binaries of white elite and indigenous poor. In their family relationships, political activism, and community life, the new middle class confronted competing moral imperatives.Focusing on social and political struggles that hinged on class and racial status in a provincial boomtown in central Bolivia, Shakow recounts the experiences of first-generation teachers, agronomists, lawyers, and prosperous merchants. They puzzled over whom to marry, how to claim public interest in the face of accusations of selfishness, and whether to seek political patronage jobs amid high unemployment. By linking the intimate politics within families to regional and national power struggles, Along the Bolivian Highway sheds light on what it means to be middle class in the global south.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGroup identityzBoliviazSacaba. 0aMiddle classxPolitical activityzBoliviazSacaba. 0aPolitical culturezBoliviazSacaba. 4aFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220982240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812209822423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812209822.jpg  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Packa